%%TITLE
Costs associated with community acquired pneumonia in France.
%%ABSTRACT
Pneumocost is a prospective study that aimed at documenting the costs of the management of patients hospitalized with a pneumococcal pneumonia and the post-discharge costs during a 6-month period in the French context.Billing data were used to document hospital costs. Resource use during the follow-up period was collected through phone interviews at month 1, 3 and 6. Descriptive statistics and multivariate analyses were performed. We used generalized linear models with log-link functions to estimate parameters associated with hospital and follow-up costs of patients.Five hundred twenty-four patients were enrolled in 40 public centers from October 2011 to April 2014. Average age was 63 (SD 17); 55.0% of them were male. Average length of stay was 15Â days (SD 23). Average cost of stay for the French Sickness Fund was â‚¬7293 (SD â‚¬7363). Average cost of follow-up was â‚¬1242 (SD â‚¬3000) and decreased steadily through time. When controlling for patient's socioeconomic characteristics, severity of disease and hospital stay, results showed a concave relationship between hospital costs and age. Obesity, the severity of the disease and comorbidities were associated with constantly increasing inpatient costs. Concerning follow-up costs, we found the same concave relationship with age, while gender, a history of pneumonia and severity of the disease were the most important predictors of high costs after discharge.Pneumocost is the first French study providing a robust estimation of the cost of managing invasive pneumococcal pneumonia in the French context.
%%METHODS
This prospective, multicentric, observational study enrolled patients hospitalized for confirmed pneumococcal CAP from October 2011 to April 2014 at 38 public hospital centers in France. The Consultative Committee for the Treatment of Information in Health Research (CCTIRS) and the French Data Protection Authority (CNIL) approved the study.
Study population and data collection
Patients enrolled in the Pneumocost study were adults aged at least 18 years old with CAP confirmed at admission by X-ray and Streptococcus pneumoniae confirmed with microbiological sampling. The two main diagnostic tests for the bacteriological confirmation of S. pneumoniae were pneumococcal antigenuria ? another test in 71.95% of
cases (antigenuria alone in 42.75%) and positive blood cultures in 37.98% of cases (blood culture alone in 13.93%) followed by a respiratory sampling, either deep expectoration in 13.74% (alone in 6.30%) or deep lung sampling either protected in 1.72% or unprotected in 3.63%; a few were from pleural fluid culture (4.58) or miscellaneous (5.92%).
Informed consent was required. Each center filled in the electronic case report forms with clinical profiles and cost data for each patient. Resource use during the follow-up period was collected through phone interviews.
The exclusion criteria were: pregnancy, patients inclu- ded in clinical trials, patients with prior 48 h admission for other causes, and patients unable or refusing to answer the follow-up questionnaires concerning medical expenditures related to the pneumonia treatment over the 6 months after hospital discharge.
Patient data were age, sex, diagnostic criteria for pneu- mococcal CAP, microbiological identification of S. pneu- moniae, employment status, background and lifestyle, risk factors, vaccination profile, Charlson score [], Port score
[] and data related to hospitalization, admissions in intensive care and/or other intermediate and step-down care units and billing data. The Charlson comorbidity index is based on the identification of the number of comorbidities of patients using the International Classification of Diseases. The Port score is the standard pneumonia severity index used to predict mortality and morbidity in patients with pneu- monia. It combines both comorbid conditions and clinical and biological parameters recorded during the inpatient stay. The higher the score for the Charlson and the Port, the more likely the patient has a bad health status.
After discharge, resource items recorded were doctor’s visits, drugs, laboratory tests and other examinations, physiotherapy, sick leave days and re-hospitalization. Data were collected at 1 month (period 1), 3 months (period 2) and 6 months (period 3) after discharge, respectively.
Costs were calculated using tariffs and prices published by the French National Sickness Fund as a reimbursement base for insurers: public prices for drugs delivered in the outpatient setting, reference tariffs for doctor’s fees, physiotherapy, laboratory tests and other examinations. The French National Sickness Fund (Caisse Nationale d’Assurance Maladie des Travailleurs Salarie´s) is the dominant French Health Branch of the national Social Security system and covers 91% of the nationals and legal residents. The initial and subsequent hospitalization costs were calculated using the official French DRG tariff of 2014 for public hospitalizations. In the French hospital system, three categories of critical care units exist. Inten- sive care units (Unite´s des Re´animation) take care of patients with multiple organ failures, with a pejorative vital prognosis, requiring the use of artificial ventilation, renal
and hemodynamic assistance. Intermediate care units (so- called Unite´s de Soins Intensifs) are dedicated to the failure of one organ and are thus more specialized. Finally, step- down units (Unite´s de Surveillance Continue) admit patients with a moderate prognosis but require continuous monitoring. They may be used as step-down units for patients discharged from intensive care. The two last cat- egories have the same per diem tariff, whereas intensive care units are more expansive. In this article, we have sometimes grouped the three types of unit together under the label ‘‘critical care.’’
Statistical analysis
The analyses included all patients enrolled in this study. They were descriptive and explanatory (multivariate anal- yses). For each cost component, the mean, standard devi- ation (SD), minimum, maximum and median were calculated (quantitative variables). The frequencies and percentages were calculated for qualitative variables.
The statistical tests were carried out with Stata version 14: for quantitative variables, Student’s test, the Wilcoxon test or Mann-Whitney test; for categorical data, the chi2 test or Fisher exact test. These tests were two sided with a
0.05 level of significance.
Multivariate analyses aimed at establishing relationships between patients’ characteristics, patients’ care and the cost. Missing data in the follow-up period were estimated using multiple imputation models (see Supplement). Cost data presented here include missing data estimations.
